    "content": [
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Push Notifications for Async Agent Results"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Some Claude tasks take seconds; others \u2014 deep research, multi-step document analysis, code review across a large repo \u2014 take minutes. Keeping users on-screen for the full wait is poor UX. The right pattern is asynchronous: accept the task, return a job ID immediately, run Claude in a background worker, then push a notification to the device when the result is ready. This document covers the complete implementation: job submission, Expo push token registration, server-side notification dispatch using expo-server-sdk, and the in-app notification handler."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Architecture: Mobile App \u2192 Backend job queue \u2192 Anthropic SDK worker \u2192 Expo Push Service \u2192 device",
          "title": "Async agent with push notification architecture"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Why Async Matters for Claude"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Claude's API latency varies significantly by task complexity. Simple conversational replies finish in under two seconds. Multi-turn agentic workflows with tool calls, long-context document analysis, or tasks that chain multiple Claude calls can take 30 seconds to several minutes. Blocking the app UI for that duration leads to perceived crashes, background OS process kills, and users force-quitting. The async pattern decouples submission from delivery so the user can freely switch apps."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Step 1: Registering for Push Notifications"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Expo provides "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "expo-notifications"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " for token registration. Call this once at app startup (typically in a root layout effect) and store the token on your backend alongside the user ID:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "bash"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "npx expo install expo-notifications expo-device"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import * as Notifications from 'expo-notifications';\nimport * as Device from 'expo-device';\nimport Constants from 'expo-constants';\n\nexport async function registerPushToken(userId: string): Promise<void> {\n  if (!Device.isDevice) {\n    // Push tokens are not available in the iOS/Android simulator\n    console.warn('Push tokens require a physical device');\n    return;\n  }\n\n  const { status: existing } = await Notifications.getPermissionsAsync();\n  let finalStatus = existing;\n  if (existing !== 'granted') {\n    const { status } = await Notifications.requestPermissionsAsync();\n    finalStatus = status;\n  }\n  if (finalStatus !== 'granted') {\n    console.warn('Push permission denied');\n    return;\n  }\n\n  const projectId =\n    Constants.expoConfig?.extra?.eas?.projectId ?? Constants.easConfig?.projectId;\n  if (!projectId) throw new Error('Missing EAS projectId in app.json');\n\n  const { data: token } = await Notifications.getExpoPushTokenAsync({ projectId });\n\n  // Send to your backend for storage\n  await fetch('https://your-api.com/register-device', {\n    method: 'POST',\n    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },\n    body: JSON.stringify({ userId, pushToken: token }),\n  });\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "bold"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "Android extra step: "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "Android 13+ (API 33) requires an explicit runtime permission for notifications. "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "requestPermissionsAsync()"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " handles this automatically when called, but you must also add the "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "SCHEDULE_EXACT_ALARM"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " permission to "
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "marks": [
                  {
                    "type": "code"
                  }
                ],
                "text": "app.json"
              },
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": " if scheduling local notifications."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "app.json Configuration"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "json"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "{\n  \"expo\": {\n    \"plugins\": [\n      [\n        \"expo-notifications\",\n        {\n          \"icon\": \"./assets/notification-icon.png\",\n          \"color\": \"#6366f1\",\n          \"sounds\": [\"./assets/notification.wav\"]\n        }\n      ]\n    ],\n    \"android\": {\n      \"googleServicesFile\": \"./google-services.json\"\n    },\n    \"extra\": {\n      \"eas\": { \"projectId\": \"<your-eas-project-id>\" }\n    }\n  }\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Step 2: Submitting a Job and Getting a Job ID"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The mobile app submits the task to your backend. The backend enqueues a worker job and immediately returns a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "jobId"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". The app stores the job ID so it can fetch the result later when the notification taps through:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// In your React Native component\nasync function submitResearchTask(query: string): Promise<string> {\n  const response = await fetch('https://your-api.com/jobs', {\n    method: 'POST',\n    headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },\n    body: JSON.stringify({\n      type: 'research',\n      query,\n      userId: currentUserId,   // backend maps this to a pushToken\n    }),\n  });\n  const { jobId } = await response.json();\n  return jobId;  // 'job_a1b2c3'\n}\n\n// Store locally so the notification handler can navigate to results\nawait AsyncStorage.setItem(`job:${jobId}`, JSON.stringify({ query, status: 'pending' }));"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Step 3: Running Claude in a Background Worker"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "The backend worker \u2014 a Node.js process using BullMQ, a Lambda, or a Supabase Edge Function \u2014 calls the Anthropic SDK and stores the result, then triggers the push. Below is a minimal Express + BullMQ pattern:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// worker.ts (Node.js)\nimport { Worker } from 'bullmq';\nimport Anthropic from '@anthropic-ai/sdk';\nimport { sendPushNotification } from './push';\nimport { db } from './db';\n\nconst client = new Anthropic();\n\nconst worker = new Worker('claude-jobs', async job => {\n  const { jobId, userId, query } = job.data;\n\n  // 1. Run Claude\n  const message = await client.messages.create({\n    model: 'claude-opus-4-8',\n    max_tokens: 4096,\n    system: 'You are a thorough research assistant. Produce a structured, factual report.',\n    messages: [{ role: 'user', content: query }],\n  });\n\n  const result = message.content[0].type === 'text'\n    ? message.content[0].text\n    : '';\n\n  // 2. Persist result\n  await db.jobs.update({\n    where: { id: jobId },\n    data: { status: 'done', result, completedAt: new Date() },\n  });\n\n  // 3. Look up push token and notify\n  const { pushToken } = await db.devices.findFirst({ where: { userId } });\n  if (pushToken) {\n    await sendPushNotification(pushToken, {\n      title: 'Your report is ready',\n      body: query.slice(0, 60) + (query.length > 60 ? '...' : ''),\n      data: { jobId },   // sent back to the app in the notification payload\n    });\n  }\n}, { connection: { host: 'localhost', port: 6379 } });"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Step 4: Sending Pushes with expo-server-sdk"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Install the server SDK in your backend:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "bash"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "npm install expo-server-sdk"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// push.ts\nimport { Expo, ExpoPushMessage } from 'expo-server-sdk';\n\nconst expo = new Expo();\n\nexport async function sendPushNotification(\n  pushToken: string,\n  opts: { title: string; body: string; data?: Record<string, unknown> }\n): Promise<void> {\n  if (!Expo.isExpoPushToken(pushToken)) {\n    console.error(`Invalid push token: ${pushToken}`);\n    return;\n  }\n\n  const messages: ExpoPushMessage[] = [{\n    to: pushToken,\n    sound: 'default',\n    title: opts.title,\n    body: opts.body,\n    data: opts.data ?? {},\n    priority: 'high',\n  }];\n\n  // Expo recommends chunking when sending to many recipients at once\n  const chunks = expo.chunkPushNotifications(messages);\n  for (const chunk of chunks) {\n    const tickets = await expo.sendPushNotificationsAsync(chunk);\n    // In production: persist tickets and poll receipts to detect failures\n    for (const ticket of tickets) {\n      if (ticket.status === 'error') {\n        console.error('Push error:', ticket.message, ticket.details);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Step 5: Handling Notifications in the App"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Register two handlers: one for notifications received while the app is in the foreground, and one for the user tapping the notification banner (which may open the app from a killed state):"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import { useEffect, useRef } from 'react';\nimport * as Notifications from 'expo-notifications';\nimport { useRouter } from 'expo-router';\n\n// Specify how foreground notifications should appear\nNotifications.setNotificationHandler({\n  handleNotification: async () => ({\n    shouldShowAlert: true,\n    shouldPlaySound: true,\n    shouldSetBadge: true,\n  }),\n});\n\nexport function usePushNotifications() {\n  const router = useRouter();\n  const responseListener = useRef<Notifications.Subscription>();\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    // Fired when user taps notification (foreground or background)\n    responseListener.current =\n      Notifications.addNotificationResponseReceivedListener(response => {\n        const jobId = response.notification.request.content.data?.jobId;\n        if (typeof jobId === 'string') {\n          router.push(`/results/${jobId}`);\n        }\n      });\n\n    return () => {\n      if (responseListener.current) {\n        Notifications.removeNotificationSubscription(responseListener.current);\n      }\n    };\n  }, []);\n}\n\n// Also handle cold-start (app was killed when notification arrived):\nexport async function handleInitialNotification() {\n  const response = await Notifications.getLastNotificationResponseAsync();\n  if (response) {\n    const jobId = response.notification.request.content.data?.jobId;\n    if (typeof jobId === 'string') {\n      // Navigate immediately after the root layout mounts\n      return jobId;\n    }\n  }\n  return null;\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Step 6: Polling for Job Status (Optional Fallback)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Push delivery is best-effort \u2014 carriers can drop notifications. Implement a lightweight polling fallback on the Results screen that checks the job status when the user opens the screen, whether they arrived via a push tap or navigated manually:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "import { useEffect, useState } from 'react';\n\nfunction useJobResult(jobId: string) {\n  const [result, setResult] = useState<string | null>(null);\n  const [status, setStatus] = useState<'pending' | 'done' | 'error'>('pending');\n\n  useEffect(() => {\n    if (!jobId) return;\n    let cancelled = false;\n\n    async function poll() {\n      while (!cancelled) {\n        const res = await fetch(`https://your-api.com/jobs/${jobId}`);\n        const data = await res.json();\n        if (data.status === 'done') {\n          setResult(data.result);\n          setStatus('done');\n          return;\n        }\n        if (data.status === 'error') {\n          setStatus('error');\n          return;\n        }\n        // Job still running \u2014 wait 5s and poll again\n        await new Promise(r => setTimeout(r, 5000));\n      }\n    }\n\n    poll();\n    return () => { cancelled = true; };\n  }, [jobId]);\n\n  return { result, status };\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Delivery Receipts and Error Handling"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Expo returns ticket objects immediately from "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "sendPushNotificationsAsync"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Tickets with "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "status: 'ok'"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " include a "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "receiptId"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ". Poll the receipts endpoint 15\u201330 minutes later to check whether APNs or FCM actually delivered the notification:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "typescript"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "// Run this periodically (e.g., a cron job)\nasync function checkReceipts(receiptIds: string[]) {\n  const chunks = expo.chunkPushNotificationReceiptIds(receiptIds);\n  for (const chunk of chunks) {\n    const receipts = await expo.getPushNotificationReceiptsAsync(chunk);\n    for (const [receiptId, receipt] of Object.entries(receipts)) {\n      if (receipt.status === 'error') {\n        if (receipt.details?.error === 'DeviceNotRegistered') {\n          // Token is stale \u2014 remove it from the database\n          await db.devices.deleteMany({\n            where: { pushToken: tokenForReceipt(receiptId) },\n          });\n        }\n        console.error(`Receipt ${receiptId} error:`, receipt.message);\n      }\n    }\n  }\n}"
          }
        ]
      },
